column1: # executed_on: 'Darwin-21.6.0-Darwin Kernel Version 21.6.0: Mon Aug 22 20:19:52 PDT

column8: predicted_definition

column2: X-linked intellectual disability due to GRIA3 anomalies
column8: A syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate intellectual disability with variable occurrence of asthenic body habitus, dysmorphic features, autistic features, macrocephaly, seizures, myoclonic jerks, and hyporeflexia that has material basis in mutation in the GRIA3 gene on chromosome Xq25.
A condition characterized by the presence of bile duct abnormalities and other symptoms.
A condition characterized by the presence of multiple congenital anomalies and dysmorphic features that are often fatal.

column2: fatal infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to mitochondrial complex I deficiency
column8: Fatal infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to mitochondrial complex I deficiency is a rare mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation disorder with complex I and IV deficiency characterized by hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, hepatic steatosis with elevated liver transaminases, exercise intolerance and muscle weakness. Neuro-opthalmological features (hemiplegic migraine, Leigh-like lesions on brain MRI, pigmentary retinopathy) have been reported later in life.

column3: A new leukoencephalopathy, the CACH syndrome (Childhood Ataxia with Central nervous system Hypomyelination) or VWM (Vanishing White Matter) was identified on clinical and MRI criteria. Classically, this disease is characterized by (1) an onset between 2 and 5 years of age, with a cerebello-spastic syndrome exacerbated by episodes of fever or head trauma leading to death after 5 to 10 years of disease evolution, (2) a diffuse involvement of the white matter on cerebral MRI with a CSF-like signal intensity (cavitation), (3) a recessive autosomal mode of inheritance, (4) neuropathologic findings consistent with a cavitating orthochromatic leukodystrophy with increased number of oligodendrocytes with sometimes ``foamy'' aspect.
column8: A rare genetic disorder characterized by progressive damage to the white matter of the brain, leading to a decline in cognitive and motor functions. It is caused by mutations in the COLEC1 gene.

column3: Autosomal recessive form of complex hereditary spastic paraplegia.
column8: Autosomal recessive form of complex hereditary spastic paraplegia.

column3: A corneal dystrophy (disease) that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A corneal dystrophy that has a syndromic presentation.

column3: A rare combined T and B cell immunodeficiency with a predisposition to lymphoproliferative syndrome. It is characterized by persistent symptomatic EBV-viremia and hypogammaglobulinemia variably presenting with fever, lymphadenopathy and systemic inflammatory conditions including hepatitis, pneumonia and sepsis. It may be associated with lymphoma, hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, and aplastic anemia.
column8: Autosomal recessive form of lymphoproliferative disease.
A group of inherited disorders characterized by abnormal keratinization of the skin, nails and hair.

column2: anomaly of puberty or/and menstrual cycle
column8: An abnormality of the ovulation cycle.
Acrodysostosis with multiple hormone resistance is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormal bone growth and resistance to several hormones.

column2: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by maternal-derived androgen
column8: A rare genetic disorder of sex development characterized by the presence of female external genitalia, but with ambiguous or underdeveloped internal reproductive structures. It is induced by maternal-derived androgen excess during pregnancy.
A form of muscular dystrophy characterized by the presence of abnormal protein aggregates in skeletal and cardiac muscle tissue.

column2: intestinal disease due to vitamin absorption anomaly
column8: An intestinal disease due to a vitamin absorption anomaly, which is rare.
A rare, aggressive form of non-Hodgkin lymphoma that originates in the skin. It is characterized by large, raised plaques or tumors on the skin, which can be painful and destructive.
Pierre Robin malformation is a sequence of developmental malformations characterized by micrognathia (mandibular hypoplasia), glossoptosis and cleft palate.
Any hereditary spastic paraplegia in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the TUBB2 gene.

column2: progressive myoclonic epilepsy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies
column8: Progressive myoclonus epilepsy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies is a rare form of progressive myoclonic epilepsy characterized by the presence of serpin-1 (neuroserpin) protein aggregates in neurons. The disease is caused by mutations in the SERPINA2 gene.
A rare type of neuroepithelial tumor that arises from the neurons in the central nervous system.
An abnormality in the appearance or position of the eyebrow.

column2: congenital muscular dystrophy with cerebellar involvement
column8: A rare genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle weakness and degeneration (atrophy), cerebellar involvement, intellectual disability, and delayed developmental milestones. It is caused by mutations in the POMGnT1 gene which encodes an enzyme involved in the synthesis of a complex carbohydrate called glycosaminoglycan.

column2: retinal ciliopathy due to mutation in the RPGR gene
column8: A retinal ciliopathy caused by a mutation in the X-linked gene, RPGR.
A neoplasm (disease) that involves the digestive system and is inherited.
A genetic disorder characterized by excessive body fat and multiple other symptoms.

column2: congenital absence/hypoplasia of fingers excluding thumb
column8: Congenital absence/hypoplasia of fingers excluding thumb is a rare developmental defect characterized by the absence or underdevelopment of all but one finger (usually the thumb). The severity can vary, with some cases involving only a few missing digits while others may have multiple absent or hypoplastic fingers.

A rare malignant neoplasm that arises from the peritoneum, which is the thin layer of tissue that lines the abdominal cavity and covers most of the organs in this area. Primary peritoneal tumors are different from other types of cancer that spread to the peritoneum.

column2: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by androgens excess
column8: A rare genetic condition in which an individual with a normal female 46, XX karyotype develops male or ambiguous genitalia and secondary sexual characteristics due to excessive exposure of the fetus to androgens during pregnancy.

column2: retinal ciliopathy due to mutation in Usher gene
column8: A type of retinitis pigmentosa characterized by the presence of cilia dysfunction, which is caused by mutation in the USH2 gene.
A structural anomaly of the respiratory system.

column2: transposition of the great arteries and conotruncal cardiac anomaly
column8: A congenital heart malformation characterized by transposition of the great arteries and a conotruncal defect.

column3: A urogenital tract malformation that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A urogenital tract malformation that is part of a larger syndrome.

column3: An inherited metabolic disease that is has its basis in the disruption of glycerol metabolic process.
column8: An inherited disorder resulting from an enzyme defect in biochemical and metabolic pathways affecting proteins, fats, carbohydrates metabolism or organelle function.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of myotilin
column8: Qualitative or quantitative defects in the protein myotilin, which is involved in muscle cell adhesion and signaling. These defects can lead to neuromuscular diseases such as congenital myopathy.

column3: A hypothyroidism that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A thyroid hormone deficiency present from birth, characterized by a specific pattern of symptoms and signs.

column2: anomaly of the secretory and excretory apparatus of the lacrimal system
column8: An anomaly of the secretory and excretory apparatus of the lacrimal system.
An inherited metabolic disease that is characterized by the impaired transport of ketone bodies in the blood.
A disorder of development or morphogenesis involving the lens induction in camera type eye.

Regional variant of Guillain-Barr√© syndrome is a rare form characterized by isolated weakness and sensory disturbances in one or more extremities, with normal reflexes. The symptoms may be preceded by an infectious illness.
A visceral malformation involving the liver, biliary tract, pancreas or spleen as part of a larger syndrome.
An acquired peripheral neurological disorder characterized by involuntary movements.
A congenital abnormality in the development of the esophagus.

column2: AP4-related intellectual disability and spastic paraplegia
column3: A disorder that presents with spastic paraplegia and intellectual disability in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the AP4B1 gene.
column8: Any syndromic intellectual disability in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in one or more of the AP4 genes (AP4B1, AP4E1, AP4M1, and AP4S1). The phenotypes observed in individuals with genetic variants in these genes are often complex and include intellectual disability, spastic paraplegia, microcephaly, brain abnormalities, and seizures.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of protein O-mannose beta1, 2N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase
column8: A qualitative or quantitative defect in the protein O-mannose beta1,2N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase involved in the glycosylation of alpha dystroglycan.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of glucosamine (UDP-N-acetyl)-2-epimerase/N-acetylmannosamine kinase
column8: A qualitative or quantitative defect in the enzyme N-acetylmannosamine kinase (GNE) can lead to a neuromuscular disease called Acid Maltase Deficiency Syndrome (AMDS).

column3: An inflammatory disease involving a pathogenic inflammatory response in the brain.
column8: A disease characterized by inflammation of the brain.
A congenital disorder characterized by underdevelopment of the facial and limb on one side.

column2: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency
column3: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency is a rare disorder of sex development due to reduced 17,20-lyase activity that affects individuals with 46,XY karyotype and is characterized by ambiguous external genitalia, including micropenis, perineal hypospadias, bifid scrotum, cryptorchidism, and a blind vaginal pouch. Blood pressure and electrolytes are normal whilst hormonal investigations show normal basal and stimulated levels of cortisol, and low basal and stimulated androgen levels.
column8: A rare form of congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency.
